Bructeri. These are found among the enemies of Varus (A. 1. 60, 4) and of Germanicus (A. 1. 51, 4, 8116..) They lived near the sources of the Ems and Lippe, and on both banks of the middle Ems (Momms. 1.1. p. 145), and were occupying this district in A.D. 58 (A. 13. 56, 4), and were important enemies in 70, when their prophetess Velaeda (see c. 8, 3) was influential. Strabo and Ptol. distinguish them into ‘mi- nores ' and ‘ maiores.'

9. Chamavos. These are found earlier near the lower Rhine (A. 13. 55, 5); their name appears to survive in that of the mediaeval district Hama- land, near Miinster. The termination, like that of ‘Batavh’ appears to be Celtic. Some have identified them with the ‘Bructeri maiores,' and sup— posed the struggle here mentioned to have been a civil war.
